post_text:
JEFCOED is very excited to launch the Jefferson County Virtual Academy of Learning (JCVAL) for students in grades K-12. Our new academy offers tuition-free, high-quality individualized learning, exemplary instruction, and regular interaction with caring online instructors. Student enrollment is available for all Alabama residents. In addition, students who are zoned to attend a JEFCOED school can participate in extracurricular activities at the school they are traditionally zoned to attend.

For more information or to begin the enrollment process visit:
https://enroll.edmentum.com/jefferson-county

PLEASE NOTE - THIS IS A FULL-TIME VIRTUAL LEARNING OPTION AND IS DIFFERENT FROM REMOTE INSTRUCTION.

Parents,

We wanted to follow up. You should have received an email/text message Monday with the survey for the 2020-2021 school year. Please select an option (traditional, remote, virtual) for each of the students in your household. If you have not received a link, please contact your local schools.

While, it is possible the traditional option might not be offered initially, we ask that you go ahead and indicate your preference. The board plans to make a final decision next week on how we will begin the school year.

Surveys are due back by the end of the day on Monday, August 3rd.

post_text:
INFORMATION ABOUT 2020-2021 SCHOOL YEAR

ROADMAP FOR PARENTS AND STUDENTS - https://bit.ly/38K3Gz4

Dear JEFCOED Family,

We are releasing our Roadmap for Parents and Students. I hope it will provide you at least some clarity about the next school year.

Also, please understand this is the first of many communications we will be sending out in the coming days and weeks. Starting next week we will be working to educate our parents and students more about these options and providing more information about other aspects associated with returning to school.

Once we finish educating our stakeholders we will be putting out a survey to parents so they can make an informed decision about their child’s future.

Thank you for your patience. I know you want all the answers. I desperately want to give you answers. However, we have to be methodical in our decision-making process.

Please stick with us.

Stay united! Stay healthy! Stay #JEFCOEDSTRONG.

We are in uncharted waters, my friends. But make no mistake, we’re going to get through this together

All the best,

Dr. G.

post_text:
Quick Message from Dr. Gonsoulin -

JEFCOED maintenance crews are hard at work building sneeze guards for the front office at each school. This is just one of several safety precautions we are working on to keep students and staff safe next fall. In addition, we are ensuring that hand sanitizing stations are available at each campus. We will also be reviewing handwashing and hygiene with students on a regular basis. Our schools will be constantly cleaned, and we will be taking steps to ensure proper social distancing. And there is even more that we will be talking about very soon! We’ll also be releasing more information in the very near future about the different school options we will be offering for 2020-21 school year. Stay tuned and stay #JEFCOEDStrong! - Dr. G

Dear JEFCOED family,

In an effort to keep you informed and be as transparent as possible, I wanted to provide you a quick update pertaining to the next school year.

We have received the state department’s reopening guidelines. At this time, my staff and I are going through that outline to customize a plan that makes sense for our district. The health and safety of our students, faculty, and staff is our top priority.

As I have stated previously, expect more information to be released sometime after July 4th. I truly appreciate your patience as we work through this process.

Sincerely,

Dr. Walter Gonsoulin
#JEFCOEDStrong

Congratulations to JEFCOED teachers Paul David Kelsey from Pleasant Grove Elementary and Alana White from Pinson Valley High School. Both are among the 16 finalists for Alabama Teacher of the Year.

“We are so proud of these two teachers. Both Paul and Alana are examples for their peers and demonstrate on a daily basis a passion for educating students. They are so deserving of being named a finalist. I wish them both continued success,” said Dr. Walter Gonsoulin, Superintendent.

Congratulations to both educators! The Alabama Teacher of the year will be announced in August.

post_text:
DON'T FORGET!!! ELIGIBLE STUDENTS HAVE UNTIL MIDNIGHT SUNDAY TO SIGN UP.

ORIGINAL POST - Jefferson County Schools is partnering with the USDA and Baylor University to deliver food straight to qualifying students’ homes.

The Emergency Meals-to-You program (eMTY) mails 10 breakfasts and 10 lunches to a student’s home every two weeks. In order to receive food, students must attend a school that qualifies based on the program’s guidelines. Students must already be enrolled in the free and reduced lunch program. Siblings (ages 1-18) of qualifying students, will also be eligible to receive the meals.

Enrollment and Eligibility Info - https://bit.ly/2Aqj86g

Emergency Meals-to-You DOES NOT replace the eight JEFCOED food distribution sites. Kikstart will continue to distribute meals at those sites Monday, Wednesday, and Friday. A complete list of the Kikstart sites is available on the JEFCOED website. Kikstart meals are available to anyone 18 and younger.

Kikstart sites - https://bit.ly/35UAIep

post_text:
Dear JEFCOED Family,

I appreciate your patience as we continue to work through the process of reevaluating our graduation plans.

Our previous plans were built around the health regulations and guidelines that were current at the time. However, when Governor Ivey and state health officials announced changes to the Safer at Home Order, we took another look. We were also waiting to see if any further guidance was issued before releasing any amended plans.

I am currently in the process of granting final approval to those plans, and you should expect a public release no later than Saturday, May 16, 2020.

Sincerely,

Dr. G

The Emergency Meals-to-You program (eMTY) mails 10 breakfasts and 10 lunches to a student’s home every two weeks. In order to receive food, students must attend a school that qualifies based on the program’s guidelines. Students must already be enrolled in the free and reduced lunch program. Siblings (ages 1-18) of qualifying students, will also be eligible to receive the meals.

Enrollment and Eligibility Info - https://bit.ly/2Aqj86g

Emergency Meals-to-You DOES NOT replace the eight JEFCOED food distribution sites. Kikstart will continue to distribute meals at those sites Monday, Wednesday, and Friday. A complete list of the Kikstart sites is available on the JEFCOED website. Kikstart meals are available to anyone 18 and younger.

Kikstart sites - https://bit.ly/35UAIep

Greetings JEFCOED Family,

Our current graduation plans are based on the state’s original Safer at Home Order. The governor announced changes to that order Friday. Due to those amendments, we will review and reevaluate our commencement plans. Just as before, we will consult with the Jefferson County Department of Health and the Alabama State Department of Education. If any changes are warranted, we will communicate them as soon as possible. Our main priority is to celebrate our students in a safe and responsible way.

Sincerely,

Dr. Walter Gonsoulin
Jefferson County Schools Superintendent

Students will be given breakfast and lunch. In order to minimize contact and maintain social distancing, the program will be curbside pickup only.

We will announce plans for the summer months at a later date.

Governor Kay Ivey and State Superintendent Dr. Eric Mackey announced today that students will not be returning to traditional school during the 2019-2020 school year. This is being done to help stop the spread of COVID-19 and to protect students, faculty, and staff. Safety continues to be our top priority.

We are expecting additional guidance from the Alabama State Department of Education, and we will communicate our district's plan to all stakeholders after we receive that information.

Please continue to observe social distancing guidelines and do everything possible to keep your family safe. We will be releasing more details in the coming days.

Dear JEFCOED Family,

While schools will officially be closed starting Thursday, March 19th, we understand many of you are concerned about students returning to class during the three days prior.

If you choose to keep your child home Monday – Wednesday, March 16th through 18th, their absences will be excused per the procedures issued by the Alabama State Superintendent of Education.

We also want to inform you that our Child Nutrition Program is currently working on a plan to feed children during the school closure. Expect more information to be released early next week.

As a reminder, Jefferson County Schools are tentatively planning to reopen on Monday, April 6th.

Sincerely,
Walter B. Gonsoulin Jr., Ph.D

post_text:
The governor has issued a state of emergency due to the Coronavirus. All schools in our state will be closed from Thursday, March 19th through Friday, April 3rd.

This means that Wednesday, March 18th will be the last day that students and staff will attend school until Monday, April 6th.

All school activities will also be cancelled during this time.

We want to be clear that there are currently no reported cases of the Coronavirus in our school system.

We will follow procedures set forth by our state leadership and health officials in the best interest of all staff and students.

Please focus on keeping your families healthy and safe.

We will be providing more detailed information in the coming days prior to the school closure.

post_text:
Approximately 300 Career Tech students from across Jefferson County Schools competed against each other in the 2nd annual JefCoEd Navigators Cup Friday.

Students who placed in each category were eligible to win up to a $5,000 scholarship to Jefferson State Community College. The Navigators cup allows students to compete in categories like industrial and electrical engineering, welding, construction, computer science, cosmetology, hospitality/tourism, and many more.

Congratulations to all the winners and thank you Jefferson State for hosting the event!

After consulting with the National Weather Service and the Jefferson County Emergency Management Agency concerning the potential of winter weather, all Jefferson County Schools will be closed on Tuesday, January 29th.

Parents, Students, Faculty and Staff:

After consulting with the National Weather Service and the Jefferson County EMA concerning the potential of severe weather during the early morning hours, all Jefferson County Schools will be delayed 2 hours on Tuesday, November 6th.

Classes will begin at 10:00 am. All teachers, local school personnel and Central Office personnel will report at 9:00 am.

Maintenance and Transportation employees will report at normal time.

All buses will run two hours later than normal. No breakfast will be served.

post_text:
Congratulations to Meghan Allen for being named the 2018-2019 Alternate Alabama Teacher of the Year and Alabama Elementary Teacher of the Year!

Meghan is an exceptional education teacher at Minor Community School who strives to prepare all students for bright futures in her self-contained classroom. “In my classroom, all students’ input is needed and valuable. We see each other for our abilities and not our disabilities. We work as a team. We build our skills to increase our independence.”

One of Meghan’s goals is to be a champion for inclusion by being a voice for all students, regardless of their special needs.

Congratulations Meghan!!!!
#thankateacher #teacherappreciationweek
Alabama Department of Education

After consulting with the National Weather Service and the Jefferson County EMA concerning the potential of severe weather, all Jefferson County Schools will close at 12:30 today. All buses will dismiss at 12:30. All after-school activities will be cancelled. All after-school daycares will be closed. All local school employees will be dismissed once students have left campus. All central office staff will be dismissed at 12:45.

Debido a la posibilidad de malas condiciones del tiempo, todas las escuelas del Sistema escolar del condado de Jefferson van a cerrar a las 12:30pm. Todos las programas y actividades extracurriculares están cancelados hoy. Todas las guardarías del niño (afterschool care) están cerradas hoy.

After consulting with the National Weather Service and the Jefferson County EMA concerning the potential of severe weather, all Jefferson County Schools will close at 12:30 today. All buses will dismiss at 12:30. All after-school activities will be cancelled. All after-school daycares will be closed. All local school employees will be dismissed once students have left campus. All central office staff will be dismissed at 12:45.
